postcontent:
New, just received from a distributor. Details are here: http://www.preciseshooter.com/Products/CZ75P01.aspx

FAQ - PLEASE READ! I am not going to respond to questions that are covered here!

Q. I am interested in your gun. Is it still available?
A. If you see this ad, most likely. The firearms are reserved for pickup on my web site, by making an appointment to buy. Someone could be doing it right now, and first person to reserve the firearm wins. Go to www.preciseshooter.com -> FAQ -> How to buy, read the requirements, and make the appointment on the site. If someone has made it just before you, I will notify you within a short time (usually, an hour), otherwise - see you shortly.

PLEASE DO NOT ASK WHETHER THE GUN IS STILL AVAILABLE! I WILL NOT RESPOND.

Q. How do I buy?
A. This is a dealer listing, NICS check, taxes, etc are all required. Please go to www.preciseshooter.com -> FAQ -> How to buy, read the requirements, and make the appointment to pick up.

Q. I am interested in your gun. Call me @ xxx-xxx-xxxx
A. Excellent. Go to www.preciseshooter.com -> FAQ -> How to buy, read the requirements, and make the appointment to pick it up.

Q. Are there any other fees, in addition to the price and taxes? NICS, background check, etc?
A. No.

Q. What is the tax rate?
A. 9.5%

Q. Where are you located?
A. Queen Anne neighborhood in Seattle.

Q. Can we meet in Burien on Monday morning?
A. No, FFL requirements are that the transfers happen at a licensed location. Also, the only times you can come over are the appointments that you can reserve on the site. No other time slots are available.

Q. I see you carry Savage rifles. Can you find me MKII FV-SR?
A. No. Please see here for what I can or cannot do: http://www.preciseshooter.com/NotInStock.aspx

Q. Do you take trades?
A. Sometimes. However:
a) firearms only,
b) they need to be our of current production (I can get new ones at wholesale prices), or you have to offer them to me at well below wholesale
c) I do not resell the trades, so they should fit my personal interests (which only include military as well as highly accurate, competition guns - no self defense guns like Glocks, M&Ps, XD*, and the like)
d) the exchange rate should be fair (see here for more: http://www.preciseshooter.com/blog/PriceGuide.aspx

Q. Is the price firm? Will you take XXX (70% of the asking price)?
A. The price is firm.

Q. Can you help me mount a scope/replace a trigger/fix a feeding problem?
A. Sorry, I do not do gunsmithing.

Q. Will you ship?
A. Yes - go to www.preciseshooter.com -> How to buy and read the section for buying outside Seattle area. Insured shipping on this gun will be $25

title: For Sale/Trade:  Remington 870 Magpul Tactical - Police - Unused
postcontent:
This is a one-of-a-kind custom built Remington 870 Tactical 12 Gauge Shotgun. Chambered for 2-3/4" & 3" shells.

The receiver is from a mid 1980's unfired 870. You will only find bluing of this quality on the Wingmaster. The internals of the action are from this same gun - unfired 1980's Remington Quality. Of course the extractor is the machined steel part like that used on the Police Model - not the molded metal extractor Remington uses on most of their 870's now. The trigger assembly is Metal - not the plastic unit that Remington uses to save $$.

The barrel is brand new from AI&P Tactical ( http://www.aiptactical.com ). It is the Remington Police barrel - 18-1/2" Factory Parkerized with Factory fixed Improved Cylinder choke (to tighten up buckshot groupings) and a Tritium Front Bead Night Sight. The magazine follower is upgraded to the S&J Hardware Tactical unit.

The forend is a Hogue Overmolded Rubber unit. The butt stock is a Magpul SGA Adjustable Length of Pull unit. This has all of the factory inserts and original packaging included to adjust the fit to you. Both are in black. I think both of these items represent the ideal combination . . . the solid feel and ergonomics of the SGA combined with the simple rubbery grip and feel of the Hogue forend.

This was built to be a no compromise simple serious reliable effective weapon. None of the frills added to make it "Tacticool".

If you bought a Factory Police Model 870 and added the stock and forend and Tritium Night Sight, the cost will be $800-$900. Even then it may not be the quality of this mid 1980's unfired Remington action/receiver.

I will throw in 25 rounds of 00 buckshot as well.

All of this at a price not much more than the cheap 870 Express tactical. If you add the items I have on this gun to the Express, you will be into it for more money and it will not be of the same quality. The cheap finish Remington puts on the Express 870 now is prone to rust rather quickly. Take a look at this gun and see the quality that Remington once built into their product. You will be the envy of all your friends when they see this shotgun in your arsenal. Just smile and let them know . . . this is a gun they will not be able to duplicate . . . and it's yours.

title: For Sale/Trade:  New in Box Kel-Tec KSG tactical Shotgun
postcontent:
This simple and reliable pump action feeds from either the left or right tube. The feed side is manually selected by a lever located behind the trigger guard.



The pump includes an under picatinny rail for the mounting of a forward grip, a light, or a laser. The included top picatinny sight rail will accept many types of optics or iron sights. Forward and rear sling loops are built in, and a basic sling is included. The soft rubber butt pad helps to tame recoil.



The KSG receiver is made from hardened steel and includes the magazine tubes which have been welded in place. The grip and stock assembly is made of glass reinforced nylon (Zytel) and is easily disassembled by pushing out 2 pins, which store in 2 holes in the grip when removed. The barrel and pump assembly is removed by loosening the 2 front magazine tube nuts with a coin and sliding the assembly forward.

title: For Sale/Trade:  WW2 Nazi p38 WITH BRINGBACK/CAPTURE PAPERWORK
postcontent:
The crown jewel of my ww2 firearms is going up for sale or trade.I think you will be hard pressed to find a p38 in this shape with documentation
I received this pistol and the man who retrieved it for the battlefield had one hell of a story.
The gentleman's name was Earl M Blodgett.He was born in 1914.He lived in Los Angeles, California.
After one year of high school he was married.On 11 January 1943 he went in to the army as part of a quartermaster detachment.
This Spreewerks walther p38 was in the hand of a german officer who was standing in defiance as an explosive device ( didn't seem to remember what device )
detonated,and the resulting shrapnel annihilated the Nazi officer.The pistol was still in his hand when Earl took it from him and two drops of blood were on the right side of the slide that Earl never cleaned off.( to spots can be seen in the bluing)He took the man's sword as well but lost it after returning home in 1946.
As a result of the shrapnel,the trigger guard and trigger were damaged slightly.
This is one of the nicest WW2 Walther P-38's you will ever see.It is a Spreewerks GmBh pistol and has Black Bakelite Grips and the magazine that was in the pistol.
This is easily in the 95% range with no rust to speak of and the fact that it has the capture/ bring back paperwork and one hell of a back story,i think ,warrants an asking price of 1200.00 obo or trade.
Feel free to make offers of cash and/or trade,part trade
I hope that this will be the crown jewel of your military collection as well and that you will give it a good home.
I am going in a different direction with my collection
